That's right! Elastic fibres can be found in elastic CT. In the absence of fibrillin (i.e in elastic artery), elastic fibres form fenestrated sheets, which resemble lasagne noodles in the image.

Elastin    tissue resiliency; found in structures that must stretch under pressure & recoil. Elastin molecules, elaborated on a scaffold of fibrillin microfibers, forms elastic fibres.  In the absence of fibrillin, elastin molecules form fenestrated      sheets.
Elastic fibres are found with collagen fibres in i) loose areolar CT and ii) dense CT structures such as elastic ligaments (e.g. ligamenta flava). 
In certain blood vessel, such as aorta (seen here), elastin produces by smooth muscle cells forms elastic lamellae.
having perforations, apertures, or transparent areas

The aorta experiences extraordinary pressures during the systolic phase of the cardiac cycle. Because of its resiliency, it will stretch in response to these peaks in pressure and bounce back as the pressure drops during diastole. 

This resiliency is due to the presence of fenestrated sheets of elastin (arrows) in its walls     .
The sheets of elastin are identifiable by their wavy appearance, like sheets of lasagne between the layers of smooth muscle.
